pr_review_comment_body:
That's a good question. At first glance the `@set_params` and `@pytest.mark.parametrize` decorators seem equivalent but they work in very different ways. I had a look at the latter before I implemented the former and realized it didn't suit the purpose I had in mind.

`@pytest.mark.parametrize` is used to inject different values into a test method's parameter. Each value will trigger a new execution of the test. For example, consider the following test method:
```
@pytest.mark.parametrize('auto_offset_reset', ['earliest', 'latest'])
@pytest.mark.parametrize('enable_auto_commit', [True, False])
def test_consumer(kafka_consumer, auto_offset_reset, enable_auto_commit)
    ...
```
This method will run 4 times, each time with the following values for the `(auto_offset_reset, enable_auto_commit)` variables: `('earliest', True)`, `('earliest', False)`, `('latest', True)`, `('latest', False)`.
The `kafka_consumer` fixture, however, **will be instantiated the same way every time**. The parameters above are injected into the test method, but not the fixture itself.

The `@set_params` decorator does not cause multiple test executions. Instead, it just passes parameters for the instantiation of the specified fixture. In the example below, the test is run only once and the parameters specified in the `@set_params` call are injected into the `kafka_consumer` fixture, not the test method:
```
@set_params(kafka_consumer={'auto_offset_reset':'earliest', 'enable_auto_commit':True})
def test_consumer(kafka_consumer)
    ... kafka_consumer is intantiated with the parameters specified above^^
```

There's indeed room to be more graceful, I considered that also (or even with`--flat` & `--nested` options), but opted for the `--json-tree` option because:
* pipenv graph is mostly an interface to pipdeptree;
* abstracting pipdeptree's arguments away would add a layer of confusion (in it's usage but also for developments down the road);
* future versions of pipdeptree could add more arguments, which could conflict with pipenv's own graph commands;
* it would mean more code will have to be maintained.

I also considered exposing `--graph-output`, but that didn't seem justified in a Dev & CI/CD environment.

@symbolist : Please correct me if I am wrong.

I think this is why we are using "INSERT ON DUPLICATE UPDATE" query in mysql. If there will be any object(whose value is already present in the database) and it is being inserted, it will be updated with new values for `earned`, `total`, `percent` and `last_modified`. Another point to support this, when we use `submit_completion`, which internally uses `create_or_update`. It returns a flag which tells if the new object was created or not. In the present codebase, there is no support for such case.

Also since the `Aggregator` objects are not saved, `created` and `modified` will not be populated before being saved to db.
